<section class="learning-objectives" id="sect-00001">
<title>Learning Outcomes</title>
<para id="para-00001">By the end of this section, you will be able to:</para>
<list id="list-00001">
<item>Describe barriers that negatively impact health outcomes.</item>
<item>Examine factors that influence participation in health promotion activities.</item>
<item>Recognize opportunities for health promotion and disease prevention across health care settings.</item>
<item>Explain how systems can serve as barriers to effective disease prevention and health promotion.</item>
</list>
</section>
<para id="para-00002">Many factors influence the health of individuals and communities. A <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00001">barrier</term> is a circumstance or obstacle that keeps people from progressing toward achieving a positive health outcome. Barriers to health promotion and disease prevention exist at various levels, including the individual level, family level, system level, and community or population level. The health care setting may even present barriers. On the other hand, communities provide many opportunities for health promotion and disease prevention, particularly within health care. Nurses who understand barriers can capitalize on available opportunities.</para>
<section id="sect-00002">
<title>Barriers to Health Promotion and Disease Prevention</title>
<para id="para-00003">It is necessary to be aware of barriers to plan to overcome them for clients or populations. These include barriers to economic stability, access to high-quality education, and access to quality health care. Other barriers are related to neighborhood and <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00002">built environment</term> and to social and community contexts. These barriers can also contribute to <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00003">health disparities</term>, as described in <link document="m00146">Chapter 9, Health Disparities and Inequities</link>. As discussed, the SDOH are barriers that can prevent an individual from obtaining the resources they need to achieve better health outcomes and improved quality of life (Healthcare Information and Management Systems Society, 2020). (See <link document="m00140">Chapter 8, Social Determinants Affecting Health Outcomes</link>.) <link target-id="table-00001" document="m00182"/> provides individual and system-level examples of barriers to health promotion and disease prevention that may occur within each area of the SDOH.</para>

